{{Infobox writer <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].--> | name = Henricus Hornkens | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = 1612 <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = clergyman | language = French, Spanish, Latin | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = [[Baroque]] | genre = Lexicography | subject = <!-- or: | subjects = --> | movement = | notableworks = ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=3lUtAIb15-YC Recueil de dictionnaires françoys, espagnols et latins]'' (1599) | spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = --> | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} '''Henricus Hornkens''', sometimes cited as '''Henri''' or '''Heinrich''' (died 1612) was a 16th-century priest and lexicographer.
==Life== Hornkens served [[Philip II of Spain]] and [[Philip III of Spain]] as a court chaplain. In 1598 he accompanied the Infanta [[Isabella Clara Eugenia]] to the [[Spanish Netherlands|Low Countries]], where he became dean of the church of St Gummarus in [[Lier, Belgium|Lier]], [[Duchy of Brabant]]. He compiled a French-Spanish-Latin dictionary that was published in Brussels in 1599 and was used by [[César Oudin]] in his own lexicographical work. He died in 1612.<ref>Emile Van Arenbergh, "Hornkens (Henri)", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2050.pdf vol. 9](Brussels, 1887), 519.</ref>
